{{Infobox book | name = Inside the Atom | image = Inside the Atom - bookcover.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = 1974 edition cover | author = [[Isaac Asimov]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Atomic physics]] | genre = [[Popular science]] | published = [[New York City]] | publisher = [[Abelard-Schuman]] | pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = 176 pp. | awards = | isbn = | oclc = | notes = }}
'''''Inside the Atom''''' is a [[popular science]] book by American author [[Isaac Asimov]]. The first edition of the book was published in 1956 by [[Abelard-Schuman]]. Revised editions were brought out in subsequent years.<ref name="Science Newsletter">{{cite journal|title=Books of the Week|journal=The Science News-Letter|date=13 September 1958|volume=74|issue=11|page=172}}</ref>
==Overview== The book describes the internal structure of the [[atom]]. The sequence of concepts described in the book follows the sequence that those facts were discovered in. It describes the various sub-atomic structures within the atom, and the functions they fill in the whole structure.<ref name=Bruce>{{cite journal|last1=Bruce|first1=Guy V.|title=Inside the Atom by Isaac Asimov|journal=The Clearing House|date=September 1957|volume=32|issue=1|pages=48–49|jstor=30180040}}</ref> Later chapters describe [[chemical element]]s and [[isotopes]], the stability and instability of [[atomic nuclei]], and finally [[atomic energy]], the uses it has, and the threat that it poses.<ref name="Science Newsletter"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Inside the Atom|journal=Bulletin from Virginia Kirkus' Service|date=1 May 1956}}</ref> A review in the educational journal ''The Clearing House'' said that the book was "lucid", and that its "analytical style exemplifies the art of good teaching." The book is aimed at educated lay-readers, and high-school science students.<ref name=Bruce/> ''Inside the Atom'' ends on a cautionary note, stating "If only we can learn to use the knowledge we already have..."
In 1956, the book was used in a pilot program to advance science education sponsored by the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]. Approximately two hundred titles were circulated amongst high schools that did not have adequate science reading material.<ref name=Deason>{{cite journal|last1=Deason|first1=Hilary J.|title=Traveling High-School Science Libraries|journal=Science |series=New Series|date=23 November 1956|volume=124|issue=3230|pages=1013–1017|jstor=1753196}}</ref>
